      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The idea that a smaller, more targeted safety net would automatically boost participation is a common but often overlooked argument in policy debates. While some economists support the \"work-first\" approach to minimize disincentives, others warn that drastic cuts could increase poverty, instability, and ultimately depress overall economic productivity. The consensus is that the solution likely lies in redesigning the system to better support work—such as aligning benefit phases with job search timelines—rather than simply removing support entirely. Therefore, claiming current support actively undermines efficiency is too simplistic because the system also provides crucial stability that keeps people from falling into destitution.",
